Nearly a hundred years later² there was published in London (1675 : Mr. Housman says 1674, but my copy is dated 1675) Edward Sherburne⁷s translation of, and commentary upon, Book Ι. It is surprising how many of the countrymen of Newton have pleased themselves with Manilius, and if only as the first of them Sherburne deserves gratitude. But he deserves gratitude on other grounds also. His translation (which is in heroic verse) is not good, but it is not bad. As verse it has a good many of the merits of the verse of the time. As a rendering of Manilius it is pretty honest, not freer than Pingre and not much less accurate. But it is the notes to this translation which chiefly deserve praise. Of the Latin text Sherburne has nothing to say,3 but around his English rendering of it he has massed a vast collection of illustrative and explanatory matter, drawn from all sources.
